window.docContents[8].resolve({"/Replete-categories/Weakly-contractible-categories/#Pro-___tale-cohomology--Replete-categories--Weakly-contractible-categories":{"contents":"From now on, we assume that pullbacks in  preserve epimorphisms.\nFor example this holds in abelian categories and (pre)topoi.\n\nAn object  of  is called weakly contractible if every\nepimorphism  has a section. We say  has enough weakly\ncontractible objects, if every object admits an epimorphism from a weakly\ncontractible one. (Bhatt–Scholze, Definition 3.2.1)\n\nUnder our assumptions on , an object  is weakly contractible\nif and only if it is projective.\n\nWe say  is locally weakly contractible, if each  in\n admits an epimorphism from the coproduct of , where\n is coherent and weakly contractible.\n(Bhatt–Scholze, Definition 3.2.1)\n\nIf  is locally weakly contractible, it has\nenough weakly contractible objects: the coproduct of projective objects is\nprojective. For example, the category of sets is locally weakly contractible.\n\nLet  have enough weakly contractible objects and  be a\nmorphism. Then  is an epimorphism if and only if for every weakly\ncontractible  in , the induced map\n is surjective.\n\nChoose an epimorphism  where  is weakly contractible\nand lift that to .\n\nIf  has enough weakly contractible objects, it is replete.\n\nThis follows from , the fact that\n commutes with limits and the corresponding statement in\nthe category of sets.\n\n","context":"Pro-étale cohomology\u0009Replete categories","header":"3.2. Weakly contractible categories","id":"/Replete-categories/Weakly-contractible-categories/#Pro-___tale-cohomology--Replete-categories--Weakly-contractible-categories"}});